    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I pay more for certified organic or biodynamic natural wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Certification adds $2-8 to production costs, which justifies modest price premiums, but many excellent natural wine producers practice organic/biodynamic methods without certification. Focus on the producer's actual farming practices rather than certifications—small producers like Dard & Ribo or COS make outstanding natural wines without formal certification. The premium should reflect genuine quality improvements from better fruit, not just marketing appeal.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do natural wine prices compare to conventional wines of similar quality?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Natural wines typically cost 20-40% more than conventional wines due to lower yields, hand-harvesting, and more labor-intensive cellar work. A $25 natural wine often matches the quality and complexity of a $35-45 conventional wine, especially regarding terroir expression and aging potential. The price difference narrows at higher price points, where conventional wines also employ similar careful techniques and vineyard management practices.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the sweet spot price range for natural wines that age well?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Natural wines with serious aging potential typically start around $35-50, where producers can afford the vineyard selection and cellar time necessary for structured, age-worthy wines. Look for natural wines from traditional regions like Burgundy, Northern Rhône, or Barolo, where established terroir and winemaking knowledge create wines that develop beautifully over 10-20 years. Avoid paying aging wine prices for simple, drink-now natural wines regardless of producer hype.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are expensive natural wines from famous producers always worth the premium?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Established natural wine pioneers like Marcel Lapierre, Domaine de la Côte, or Gravner command high prices based on proven track records and exceptional vineyard sites, making them generally worthwhile investments. However, many newer producers charge similar prices based on marketing rather than substance—research their vineyard sources, winemaking experience, and critical reviews. The best value often comes from established producers' entry-level bottlings rather than newcomers' flagship wines.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How should I budget for building a natural wine collection?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Allocate 60% of your budget to $20-35 bottles for regular drinking, 30% to $40-60 bottles for special occasions, and 10% to premium bottles over $60 for cellaring or rare producers. Start with versatile regions like Loire Valley Chenin Blanc or Beaujolais Cru, which offer excellent value and food-pairing flexibility. Consider joining natural wine clubs or buying directly from importers to access better prices and allocation wines not available at retail.</p>
